node.text:
2 months ago I was out in Los Angeles and I saw this homeless artist doing these beautiful drawings. I thought to myself, wow this guy is super talented and could really be successful but just doesn’t have the tools to succeed and it sucks that life isn’t fair sometimes. I thought, I’ll make him an Instagram account and help him post all of his artwork on it and get my followers to follow him. Social media changed my entire life and I wanted it to do the same for him. I taught him how to use it, and I posted his work on my Tik Tok and Instagram and told everyone to please follow this talented artist @Dustnbonesart. Within 2 days he had 121,000 followers. 

Today, he has 157,000 followers. He’s no longer homeless. He has a manager (thank you @roniemanhattan!!!). He’s sponsored by Arizona (thank you @drinkarizona!!!) He’s getting flown out to do murals for businesses. He’s selling out all of his drawings. And he’s fulfilling his dream of making his own comic!!

In September, his first comic will be done. 10,000 print run. Standard 24 page comic. It will be called “Edge of the Galaxy”. Please follow him, support him and grab one of his comics when they’re released! @Dustnbonesart @Dustnbonesart @Dustnbonesart

node.text: Thank you to @roniemanhattan for putting together this beautiful film for @dustnbonesart. He now has a gofundme setup if anyone wants to help him get on his feet and live out his dreams of making a living as an artist. Let’s show him the power of social media ♥️ Click the link in my bio to donate to his gofundme.

node.text: I met a very talented artist yesterday that happened to be homeless. I figured I’d make him an Instagram account and shout him out so that the world can see his beautiful work. I taught him how to use it and now he’s posting everyday on his own. It’s only been 2 days and he already has over 100K followers!!! He’s overwhelmed with joy ♥️ I visited him today to see how he’s handling his newly found fame. I cannot believe how kind all of you are and how much support you’ve all given him. Thank you all so much! I wanted to give everyone an update. It’s incredible what a community can do with a little bit of love and compassion ♥️ Follow @dustnbonesart, also he just got a Venmo account if anyone wants to donate and help him get on his feet! Imagine what could happen if we each just sent him a dollar 🥺 (Venmo: @dustnbonesart)  the name Andrew Shaffner should come up on Venmo

node.text: I’m out here in LA and I met this homeless artist and I wanted to give him an Instagram shoutout so that people can follow him and support him. He didn’t have Instagram so I bought a drawing instead and posted his work to my story. I’m getting soooo many DM’s from people telling me that he’s incredible and they would love to buy his work so I went back to find him and luckily he was still there. He says he’s always there all day if you would like to support a homeless artist. He draws right in front of Dash Radio - 6363 Hollywood Blvd, Los Angeles. 🔥DUST-N-BONES🔥 #supportartists UPDATE: I made him an Instagram, FOLLOW @dustnbonesart, also he just got a Venmo account if anyone wants to donate and help him get on his feet! Imagine what could happen if we each just sent him a dollar 🥺 (Venmo: @dustnbonesart) the name Andrew Shaffner should come up on Venmo

node.text:
4 months ago I was visiting LA and I came across this super talented artist sitting outside working on some drawings. I wanted to post his drawings on my Instagram and get him some followers but he told me that he was homeless and didn’t have an Instagram. So I sat with him and explained the power of social media and explained how it’s changed my life. I asked him if I could make him an account and he agreed.
So I made him an account, and taught him how to use it (@dustnbonesart). I told him to promise to keep up with posting his work so that he can get some business and sell some of his drawings. He said he would. So we photographed all of his work together and posted all of them. I then made a post and told all of my followers to follow him. Within 2 days he gained 121,000 followers. His dream in life was to create his own comic book, and @drinkarizona took notice of his story and sponsored his dream.

A few months later, he’s no longer homeless and has been working diligently on his 1st comic book. Finally, his first comic book “Edge of the Galaxy” is complete and I am so proud of him! He kept his promise and kept up with posting on his Instagram, so I’m keeping my promise when I told him that I’ll help him promote it when it’s for sale. And, finally, after months of hard work & dedication it’s up and ready to pre order!!

Click on the link on his bio (@dustnbonesart) to reserve your copy!! 🔥🔥🔥

When you’re blessed, don’t raise your standards of living, raise your standards of giving ♥️

Like Edit profile Edit profile Artist. Instagram @devonrodri Nyc artist evonrodriguezartist@gmail.co'.

node.text: I always drew and painted strangers on the NYC subway. If you scroll down to the bottom of my Instagram feed, you’ll see evidence of that since 2014. It was always my genuine passion. I always loved to people watch. I also always loved to draw. I always found people interesting and always thought deeply about how people behave and how we interact with eachother. I always felt like I was analyzing people’s psychology. I found myself analyzing myself as well. And I always had this deep need to become successful. It’s all I thought about ever since I was like 5 years old. It’s always been a mindset of “I know I’ll be a famous artist, but how and when?” In June 2020 while we were all locked up in our homes, I kept seeing the excitement of TikTok all over the internet. I kept seeing all of these teenagers become mega viral and it was so inspiring to me. Not taking the traditional route and doing something different has always been super inspiring to me. No matter how many times the adults in my life told me not to drop out of college, I always thought “no! It’s a new era and I’ll make it through social media.” Also, I was living in the South Bronx in my grandma’s home. She saved me from my mother’s abusive home in 2011 and no one knew what life was like for me growing up so I didn’t think their advice was relevant to me. So June 2020, during the height of the pandemic I found myself in bed a lot at 3am thinking “how will I become the successful artist that 5 year old me always expected me to be?” So I joined TikTok. I tried posting a video of myself on painting one of my portrait commissions. I got 500 views. Not bad, but not enough to satisfy my ambition. I thought “maybe I should paint celebrities”, which I never did before because I didn’t think it was genuine. I always loved real people. (continue reading in the comments)

node.text: @Uniqlousa is celebrating 15 years in SoHo (546 Broadway New York, NY)– join me in celebrating this Thursday 8/26 from Noon-4PM. I’ll be there (2-4pm) along with Tiger Hood, Mona Matsuoka will be DJing and we’ll be serving Prince Street Pizza to all. As an added bonus, if you show the Uniqlo app on your phone in store, you’ll be entered into a drawing to win prizes including a custom portrait by yours truly! #UQUS15in5
